<!-- Single-Threaded Language

JavaScript is a single-threaded language, which means it has only one 
call stack and can execute only one task at a time. It processes code 
sequentially, executing one statement before moving to the next.
Because JavaScript runs on a single thread, if a task takes a long
time to complete, it can block the execution of other code. To handle 
operations such as API requests, timers, and file operations efficiently,
JavaScript uses asynchronous programming, along with features like
the Event Loop, Callbacks, Promises, and Async/Await.
For example, when JavaScript encounters a setTimeout() or an API call, 
it delegates the task to browser or runtime APIs and continues 
executing other code. Once the task is complete, its callback 
is placed in a queue and executed when the call stack becomes empty. -->





<!-- Synchronous Code in JavaScript

Synchronous code executes one statement at a time in sequence. 
JavaScript waits for the current operation to finish before moving 
to the next one, so each task blocks the execution of the tasks that follow it.
This type of execution is simple and predictable because the code runs 
from top to bottom in order. However, if a task takes a long time to 
complete, the entire program must wait, which can make the application 
less responsive. -->





<!-- Asynchronous Code in JavaScript

Asynchronous code is code that allows JavaScript to start a task 
and continue executing other code without waiting for that task to 
finish. Instead of blocking the program, the result of the task is 
handled later when it becomes available.
Asynchronous programming is commonly used for operations that 
take time, such as API requests, database queries, file reading, 
and timers. This helps keep applications responsive and prevents 
the program from freezing while waiting for these operations to complete.
For example, when using setTimeout() or fetching data from an API, 
JavaScript continues executing the remaining code and processes 
the result once the operation is finished. -->





<!-- Async Function in JavaScript

An async function is a special type of function that allows you 
to work with asynchronous operations more easily using the await 
keyword. It helps write asynchronous code in a way that looks and 
behaves like synchronous code, making it easier to read and understand.
When a function is declared with the async keyword, it automatically 
returns a Promise. Inside an async function, the await keyword can 
be used to pause the function's execution until a Promise is resolved, 
without blocking the rest of the program.

Example:

async function getData() {
    const data = await fetch("https://api.example.com/data");
    console.log("Data received");
}

In this example, await waits for the data to be fetched before 
moving to the next line, while other JavaScript code can continue running. -->





<!-- Promise in JavaScript

A Promise is an object that represents the eventual result of 
an asynchronous operation. It acts as a placeholder for a 
value that may not be available immediately but will be available 
at some point in the future.

A Promise can be in one of three states:

Pending – the operation is still in progress.
Fulfilled (Resolved) – the operation completed successfully.
Rejected – the operation failed.

Promises help manage asynchronous code more effectively than 
callbacks and can be handled using .then(), .catch(), and async/await.

Example:
const promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    resolve("Success");
});

promise.then((result) => {
    console.log(result);
});

In this example, the Promise is resolved with the value "Success", 
and the .then() method receives and prints that value. -->





<!-- Execution Context in JavaScript

An Execution Context is the environment in which JavaScript 
code is executed. It contains all the information needed to run 
the code, including variables, functions, and the value of this.
Whenever JavaScript executes a script or calls a function, 
it creates an execution context. The execution context determines 
what code is currently being executed and provides access to the 
necessary data for that code.

There are mainly two types of execution contexts:

Global Execution Context (GEC) – Created when the JavaScript program starts. 
It is the default execution context and is created only once.
Function Execution Context (FEC) – Created every time a function is invoked. 
Each function call gets its own execution context.

The execution context is created in two phases:

Memory Creation Phase – JavaScript allocates memory for variables and 
functions. Variables are initialized with undefined, and function 
definitions are stored completely.
Execution Phase – JavaScript executes the code line by line and assigns 
actual values to variables. -->





<!-- Blocking Code vs Non-Blocking Code in JavaScript

Blocking code is code that prevents the execution of other 
code until the current task is completed. JavaScript waits 
for the operation to finish before moving to the next statement. 
Long-running calculations or synchronous operations are examples 
of blocking code.

Non-blocking code is code that allows JavaScript to continue 
executing other tasks without waiting for the current operation to complete. 
The operation runs asynchronously, and its result is handled later through 
callbacks, Promises, or async/await.

For example, a large loop that takes several seconds to complete 
is blocking because the program cannot do anything else until the 
loop finishes. On the other hand, setTimeout() is non-blocking because 
JavaScript schedules the task and immediately continues executing the 
remaining code. -->





